  <subsection>
    <title>Planes in Space</title>
    <p>
      Now that we have a way of describing lines, we would like to develop a means of describing planes in three dimensions. In <xref ref="S-Precalc-3Dcoord">Section</xref>, we studied the coordinate planes and planes parallel to them. In particular, fundamental planes were of the form <m>coordinate = constant</m>, like <m>x=1, y=-2, \text{or} z=\sqrt{3}</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fundamentalplanewithvector">
      <caption>A plot of <m>x=1</m> in red, <m>y=-2</m> in blue, and <m>z=\sqrt{3}</m> in green with a normal vector plotted for each fundamental plane</caption>
      <interactive title="interactive-fundplanewvect" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
          var('t,s')
          plot6=axes(3,1,color="black")+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30)
          plot6+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,sqrt(3)),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),color="green",opacity=.25,frame=False,mesh=True,plot_points=2)
          plot6+=parametric_plot3d((1,t,s),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),color="red",opacity=.25,frame=False,mesh=True,plot_points=2)
          plot6+=parametric_plot3d((s,-2,t),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),frame=False,mesh=True,plot_points=2,color="blue",opacity=.25)
          plot6+=arrow((2,2,sqrt(3)),(2,2,sqrt(3)+1),color="green",width=3)
          plot6+=arrow((1,2,0),(2,2,0),color="red",width=3)
          plot6+=arrow((-0.5,-2,1),(-0.5,-1,1),color="blue",width=3,aspect_ratio=1)
          plot6
        </slate>
      </interactive>
      </figure>
    <p>  
      As shown in <xref ref="fundamentalplanewithvector"/>, any vector in a plane with <m>x= \text{constant}</m> will be orthogonal to the vector <m>\langle 1,0,0 \rangle</m>, any vector in a plane with <m>y= \text{constant}</m> will be orthogonal to the vector <m>\langle 0,1,0 \rangle</m>, and any vector in a plane with <m>z= \text{constant}</m> will be orthogonal to the vector <m>\langle 0,0,1 \rangle</m>. We will use this idea to define a plane in general.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>plane</term><idx><h>plane</h><h>definition</h></idx> <m>p</m> in space is the set of all terminal points of vectors emanating from a given point <m>P_0</m> perpendicular to a fixed vector <m>\vn</m>, as shown in <xref ref="Planewithvector">Figure</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <figure xml:id="Planewithvector">
      <caption>A plot of a plane with normal vector <m>\vn</m> in red and vector on the plane <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> in orange</caption>
      <interactive title="interactive-Planewithvector" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
          var('t,s')
          scale=2
          plot7=axes(3,1,color="black",opacity=0.25)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30,frame=False)
          plot7+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,-s/2+t/3+1),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
          plot7+=arrow((1,1,5/6),(1+(1/2)*scale,1-1/3*scale,5/6+scale),color="red",width=2)
          plot7+=arrow((1,1,5/6),(-1,0,5/3),color="orange",width=2)
          plot7+=point3d((1,1,5/6),color="black",size=50)
          plot7+=text3d("P",(1.3,1.5,0.75),color="black",fontsize=30)
          plot7+=point3d((-1,0,5/3),color="black",size=50)
          plot7+=text3d("Q",(-1.2,0.5,2),color="black",fontsize=30)
          show(plot7,viewpoint=[[-0.0746,-0.4712,-0.8788],164.15],camera_position=[3.2671,9.5358,7.487])
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Like the definition of a line, the definition of a plane given above uses a starting point and a vector as the critical pieces of information. For a line, you begin at the starting point and move as much as you want parallel to the given vector (the direction vector). For a plane, you begin at the starting point and move as much as you want orthogonal to the given vector (the normal vector). For a line, you move only in the direction of the given vector whereas on a plane you cannot move at all in the direction of the given vector.
    </p>
   <!--  <figure xml:id="Planewithvector">
      <caption>A point <m>P_0</m> on a plane <m>p</m> with a normal vector <m>\vn</m></caption>
      <image width="73%" source="images/fig_9_5_plane_normal"/>
    </figure> -->

    <p>
      This description of a plane allows us to find the equation of a plane. Assume that <m>\vn=\langle a,b,c\rangle</m>, <m>P = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m>, and that <m>Q=(x,y,z)</m> is an arbitrary point on the plane. Since the vector <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> lies in the plane, it must be perpendicular to <m>\vn</m>. This means that
      <md>
        <mrow>0 =\mathstrut \amp  \vn\cdot\overrightarrow{PQ}</mrow>
        <mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \vn\cdot \big(\langle x,y,z \rangle - \langle x_0, y_0,
            z_0\rangle\big)</mrow>
        <mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \vn \cdot \langle x-x_0, y-y_0, z-z_0 \rangle</mrow>
        <mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0).</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      The fixed vector <m>\vn</m> perpendicular to the plane is frequently called a <em>normal vector</em> to the plane. We may now summarize our new equation for a plane. 
    </p>

    <assemblage xml:id="Plane-scalar-equation">
      <title>Equations of a plane</title>
      <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <em>scalar equation</em> of the plane<idx><h>plane</h><h>scalar equation</h></idx> with normal vector <m>\vn =\langle a,b,c \rangle</m> containing the point <m>P = (x_0, y_0,z_0)</m> is
            <men xml:id="eq_9_5_plane_norm">
              a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0.
            </men>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The <em>vector equation</em> of the plane<idx><h>plane</h><h>vector equation</h></idx> with normal vector <m>\vn =\langle a,b,c \rangle</m> containing the points <m>P = (x_0, y_0,z_0)</m> and <m>Q = (x,y,z)</m> is
            <men xml:id="eq_9_5_plane_norm_vector">
              \vn \cdot \overrightarrow{PQ} = 0.
            </men>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    </assemblage>
    <p>
      We may take the scalar equation of a plane a little further and note that since
      <me>
        a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0,
      </me>
      it equivalently follows that
      <me>
        ax + by + cz = ax_0+by_0+cz_0.
      </me>
      That is, we may write an equation of a plane as <m>ax+by+cz = d</m> where <m>d = \vn\cdot\langle x_0,y_0,z_0\rangle</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before we look at some examples, we will mention a few ideas that relate planes (as a collection of points), equations for these planes, and normal vectors for these planes. As we saw with lines and will see for most other types of graphs, there is not a unique way to give an equation for a plane. This highlights the difference between an equation that describes a graph and the set of points that make up the graph or make the equation true. For instance, <m>x+y+z=1</m> and <m>2x+2y+2z=2</m> are different equations but describe the same graph (have the same set of <m>(x,y,z)</m> points that make the equation a true statement.) You may be tempted to say <q>Those are the same equations. They just differ by a scalar multiple!</q>, but this difference is the same as the difference between parallel vectors. 
    </p>
    <p>
      The good news is that the orientation of a plane is encoded into the normal vector, thus we can use all the powerful tools we developed for vectors. We say that two planes are <term>parallel</term> if their normal vectors are parallel (as vectors). In fact, we can describe the angle between two planes using normal vectors. The angle between two planes is the acute angle between their respective normal vector directions. While the angle between two vectors (as defined in <xref ref="subsec-vecangle" />) can be obtuse, the angle between planes will not be greater than <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>. When using normal vectors to describe the orientation of a plane (like when we want to measure the angle between planes), we need to consider all the vectors parallel to our choice of the normal vector because any vector parallel to our choice would give an equivalent equations for the plane. We will look at specifics of this in our next example. 
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        If we would like to describe the plane passing through the point <m>P=(4,-2,1)</m> and perpendicular to the vector <m>\vn = \langle 1, 2, 1 \rangle</m>, we have
        <me>
          \langle 1,2,1 \rangle\cdot \langle x,y,z\rangle = \langle 1,2,1 \rangle\cdot \langle 4,-2,1\rangle
        </me>
        or
        <me>
          x + 2y + z = 1.
        </me>
        Notice that the coefficients of <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m> in this description give a vector perpendicular to the plane. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="exampleplane1">
        <caption>A plot of a plane with normal vector <m>\vn</m> in red and vector on the plane <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> in orange</caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-exampleplane1" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
            var('t,s')
            plot8=axes(3,1,color="black",opacity=0.5)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30,frame=False)
            plot8+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,1-s-2*t),(s,-2,2),(t,-2,2),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.5,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot8+=arrow((0,0,1),(0+(1),0+2,1+1),color="red",width=2)
            plot8+=text3d("&lt;1,2,1&gt;",(1.2,2.5,2.5),color="red",fontsize=25)
            show(plot8,viewpoint=[[-0.4579,-0.5809,-0.673],124.11],camera_position=[15.3888,4.2661,3.2235])
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        For instance, if we are presented with the plane
        <me>
          -2x + y - 3z = 4,
        </me>
        we know that <m>\vn = \langle -2, 1, -3\rangle</m> is a vector perpendicular to the plane.
      </p>
      <p>
        Using our definition of parallel planes, we can see that our plane given by <m>x+2y+z=1</m> will be parallel to planes given by <m>x+2y+z=-2</m>, <m>2x+4y+2z=1</m>, and <m>-\frac{3}{2}x-3y-\frac{3}{2}z=12,345</m> because the respective normal vectors (<m>\langle1,2,1\rangle</m>, <m>\langle1,2,1\rangle</m>, <m>\langle2,4,2\rangle</m>, and <m>\langle -\frac{3}{2},-3,-\frac{3}{2}\rangle</m>) are all scalar multiples of each other. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="parallelplanes">
        <caption>A plot of three parallel planes with normal vectors</caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-parallelplanes" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
            var('t,s')
            plot11=axes(3,1,color="black",opacity=0.5)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30,frame=False)
            plot11+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,1-s-2*t),(s,-1.5,1.5),(t,-1.5,1.5),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot11+=arrow((0,0,1),(0+(1),0+2,1+1),color="red",width=2)
            plot11+=text3d("\u27E81,2,1\u27E9",(1.2,2.5,2.5),color="red",fontsize=25)
            plot11+=parametric_plot3d((s+1,t-1,1-s-2*t-2),(s,-1.5,1.5),(t,-1.5,1.5),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot11+=arrow((1,-2,-1),(1+(1),-2+2,-1+1),color="red",width=2)
            #plot11+=text3d("\u27E81,2,1\u27E9",(1.2,2.5,2.5),color="red",fontsize=25)
            plot11+=parametric_plot3d((s-3,t-1,1-s-2*t),(s,-1.5,1.5),(t,-1.5,1.5),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot11+=arrow((-3,-1,1),(-3+(-2),-1+(-4),1-2),color="red",width=2)
            plot11+=text3d("\u27E8-2,-4,2\u27E9",(-5.5,-5.5,2.5),color="red",fontsize=25)
            show(plot11,viewpoint=[[0.3135,-0.6034,-0.7333],221.71],camera_position=[-18.6475,11.4002,4.2321])
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        If we wanted to find the angle between <m>x+2y+z=1</m> and <m>-2x+y-3z=4</m>, we would need to consider the angle between the normal vectors <m>\langle1,2,1\rangle</m> and <m>\langle -2,1,-3\rangle</m>. The dot product of these normal vectors is <m>\langle1,2,1\rangle \cdot \langle -2,1,-3\rangle=-3</m>, so the angle between these vectors is obtuse, but the (smallest) angle between the planes is NOT obtuse. The equation <m>x-\frac{1}{2}y+\frac{3}{2}z=2</m> will describe the same set of points as <m>-2x+y-3z=4</m> but the normal vector for <m>x-\frac{1}{2}y+\frac{3}{2}z=2</m> will be <m>\langle 1,-\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{2} \rangle</m>, which makes an acute angle with <m>\langle1,2,1\rangle </m>. So the angle between <m>x+2y+z=1</m> and <m>-2x+y-3z=4</m> is 
        <me>\arccos\left(\frac{\langle1,2,1\rangle \cdot \langle1,\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{2} \rangle}{\sqrt{7} \sqrt{\frac{7}{2}}}\right)\approx 1.2373</me>
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="planesangle">
        <caption>A plot of planes <m>x+2y+z=1</m> and <m>-2x+y-3z=4</m> with normal vectors</caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-planesangle" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
            var('t,s')
            plot12=axes(3,1,color="black",opacity=0.5)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30,frame=False)
            plot12+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,1-s-2*t),(s,-2.5,2.5),(t,-1.5,1.5),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot12+=arrow((0,1,-1),(0+(1),1+2,-1+1),color="green",width=2)
            plot12+=text3d("\u27E81,2,1\u27E9",(1.2,3.5,0.5),color="green",fontsize=15)
            plot12+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,(4+2*s-t)/-3),(s,-3,3),(t,-2,2),color="blue",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot12+=arrow((0,1,-1),(0+(-2),1+(1),-1+(-3)),color="blue",width=2)
            plot12+=text3d("\u27E8-2,1,-3\u27E9",(-2.5,2.5,-4.5),color="blue",fontsize=15)
            plot12+=arrow((0,1,-1),(0+(1),1+(-0.5),-1+(1.5)),color="red",width=2)
            plot12+=text3d("\u27E81,-0.5,1.5\u27E9",(1.5,2,1),color="red",fontsize=15)
            show(plot12,viewpoint=[[-0.6347,-0.6448,-0.426],134.51],camera_position=[16.9653,1.0142,-6.1312])
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        
      </p>
