    <activity xml:id="A_9_5_9">
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a scalar equation of the plane <m>p_1</m> passing through the point <m>(0, 2, 4)</m> and perpendicular to the vector <m>\vn=\langle 2, -1, 1\rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>2(x) - (y - 2) + (z - 4) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>2(x - 0) - 1(y - 2) + 1(z - 4) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is the point <m>(2, 0, 2)</m> on the plane <m>p_1</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            No, the point <m>(2, 0, 2)</m> is not on the plane <m>p_1</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Plug in <m>(2, 0, 2)</m> to the equation of the plane. Does <m>2(2) - (0 - 2) + (2 - 4) = 0</m>? No, so the point is not on the plane <m>p_1</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a scalar equation of the plane <m>p_2</m> that is parallel to <m>p_1</m> and passing through the point <m>(3, 0, 4)</m>. (Hint: Compare normal vectors of the planes.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>2(x - 3) - 1(y) + (z - 4) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Parallel planes have the same normal vector: <m>2(x - 3) - 1(y) + (z - 4) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a parametric description of the line <m>l</m> passing through the point <m>(2,0,2)</m> and perpendicular to the plane <m>p_3</m> described by the equation <m>x+2y-2z = 7</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>x(t) = 2 + t, y(t) = 2t, z(t) = 2 - 2t</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The normal vector of the plane <m>p_3</m> is <m>\langle 1, 2, -2 \rangle</m>, which will be the direction of line <m>l</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The corresponding parametric equations are <m>x(t) = 2 + t, y(t) = 2t, z(t) = 2 - 2t</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the point at which <m>l</m> intersects the plane <m>p_3</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>(3, 2, 0)</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We need to plug in the parametric equations from <m>d</m> into <m>x + 2y - 2z = 7</m> and solve for <m>t</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>(2 + t) + 2(0 + 2t) - 2(2 - 2t) = 7</m>. Solve to get <m>t = 1</m>. Plug <m>t = 1</m> into the parametric equations to get the point of intersection <m>(3, 2, 0)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
    <example>
      <p>
        Just as two distinct points in space determine a line, three non-collinear points in space determine a plane. Consider three points <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m> in space, not all lying on the same line as shown in <xref ref="exampleplane2">Figure</xref>.
      </p>

      <!-- <figure xml:id="F_9_5_Plane">
        <caption>A plane determined by three points <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m></caption>
        <image width="73%" source="images/fig_9_5_plane_3pts"/>
      </figure> -->
      <figure xml:id="exampleplane2">
        <caption>A plane determined by three points <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m></caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-exampleplane2" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            var('s,t')
            P0=(-1/2,-1/2,0)
            P1=(1/2,-1/2,0)
            P2=(-1/2,1/2,0)
            d=1.5
            plot9=parametric_plot3d((s,-s/3+t,0),(s,-d,d),(t,-d,d),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,frame=False,opacity=0.35)
            plot9+=arrow(P0,P1,color="blue")+arrow(P0,P2,color="blue")+arrow(P0,(-1/2,-1/2,1.5),color="red")
            plot9+=point(P0,size=30,color="black")+point(P1,size=30,color="black")+point(P2,size=30,color="black")
            plot9+=text3d("P\u2080",(-.75,-0.85,0.35),color="black",fontsize=25)+text3d("P\u2081",(1,-0.45,0.35),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot9+=text3d("P\u2082",(-.75,0.75,0.35),color="black",fontsize=25)
            #+text3d("p",(2.5,2,0),color="green",fontsize=25)
            plot9+=arrow(P0,(1,1,0),color="blue")+text3d("P",(1.1,1.3,0.15),color="black",fontsize=25)+point3d((1,1,0),color="black",size=30)
            plot9+=text3d("n",(-0.5,-0.5,2),color="red",fontsize=25)
            show(plot9,viewpoint=[[-0.8414,-0.2517,-0.4782],64.05],camera_position=[3.2031,-4.8751,4.9657])
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Notice that the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2}</m> both lie in the plane <m>p</m>. If we form their cross-product
        <me>
          \vn = \overrightarrow{P_0P_1} \times \overrightarrow{P_0P_2},
        </me>
        we obtain a normal vector to the plane <m>p</m>. Therefore, if <m>P</m> is any other point on <m>p</m>, it then follows that <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P}</m> will be perpendicular to <m>\vn</m>, and we have the equation:
        <men xml:id="eq_9_5_plane_vect">
          \vn \cdot \overrightarrow{P_0P} = 0
        </men>
      </p>
    </example>
    <activity xml:id="A_9_5_7">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let <m>P_0 = (1,2,-1)</m>, <m>P_1 = (1, 0 ,-1)</m>, and <m>P_2 = (0,1,3)</m> and let <m>p</m> be the plane containing <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the components of the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1} = \langle 0, -2, 0 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2} = \langle -1, -1, 4 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1} = \langle (1) - (1), (0) - (2), (-1) - (-1) \rangle = \langle 0, -2, 0 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2} = \langle (0) - (1), (1) - (2), (3) - (-1) \rangle = \langle -1, -1, 4 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a normal vector <m>\vn</m> to the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vn = \langle -8, 0, -2 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\vn = \overrightarrow{P_0P_1} \times \overrightarrow{P_0P_2} = ((-2)(4) - (0)(-1))\vi - ((0)(4) - (0)(-1))\vj + ((0)(-1) - (-1)(-2))\vj = \langle -8, 0, -2 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a scalar equation of the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>-8(x - 1) - 2(z + 1) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>-8(x - 1) + 0(y - 2) + -2(z + 1) = -8(x - 1) - 2(z + 1) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider a second plane, <m>q</m>, with scalar equation <m>-3(x-1) + 4(y+3) + 2(z-5)=0</m>.  Find two different points on plane <m>q</m>, as well as a vector <m>\vm</m> that is normal to <m>q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vm = \langle -3, 4, 2 \rangle</m>. One point on the plane is <m>(1, -3, 5)</m>. For a second point on plane <m>q</m>, choose any <m>x</m>-coordinate and <m>y</m>-coordinate, and then solve for the corresponding <m>z</m>-coordinate.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            From the scalar equation <m>\vm = \langle -3, 4, 2 \rangle</m> and the point used in the equation is <m>(1, -3, 5)</m>, which is on plane <m>q</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            For a second point on plane <m>q</m>, choose any <m>x</m>-coordinate and <m>y</m>-coordinate, and then solve for the corresponding <m>z</m>-coordinate. One such point with <m>x = 1</m>, and <m>y = -2</m> is <m>(1, -2, 3)</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The angle between two planes is the acute angle between their respective normal vectors.  What is the angle between planes <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>62.232^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The angle between the two planes is equal to the angle between the normal vectors. <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\vn\cdot\vm}{|\vn||\vm|}\right) = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{(-8)(-3) + (0)(4) + (-2)(2)}{|\sqrt{68}||\sqrt{29}|}\right) = 62.23^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>    
    </activity>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          A plane in space is the set of all terminal points of vectors emanating from a given point perpendicular to a fixed vector.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>P_1</m>, <m>P_2</m>, and <m>P_3</m> are non-collinear points in space, the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{P_1P_2}</m> and and <m>\overrightarrow{P_1P_3}</m>  are vectors in the plane and the vector <m>\vn = \overrightarrow{P_1P_2} \times \overrightarrow{P_1P_3}</m> is a normal vector to the plane. So any point <m>P</m> in the plane satisfies the equation <m>\overrightarrow{PP_1} \cdot \vn = 0</m>.  If we let <m>P = (x,y,z)</m>, <m>\vn = \langle a,b,c \rangle</m> be the normal vector, and <m>P_1 = (x_0,y_0,z_0)</m>, we can also represent the plane with the equation
          <me>
            a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    </subsection>
